TY  - JOUR
AU  - Dumas, Bernard
T1  - Dynamic Equilibrium and the Real Exchange Rate in a Spatially Separated World
PY  - 1992
Y1  - 1992/04/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/5.2.153
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 5
IS  - 2
SP  - 153
EP  - 180
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - Two homogeneous stocks of physical capital are located in two different countries, separated by an “ocean.” They are consumed by local residents, invested in a random production process yielding real returns, or transferred abroad. Under proportional transfer costs, trade, consumption, and capital imbalances are shown to be persistent. The heteroskedastic process for the relative price of capital in the two countries has a nonlinear, mean-reverting drift. Nevertheless, the conditional probability of the price moving from the parity value of unity is greater than the probability of it moving toward parity. The real interest-rate differential incorporates a simple risk premium.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/5.2.153
ER  - 



